Why the "g" is important in sed

The g flag at the end of the sed substitution command stands for global.

If you omit the g flag, sed will only replace the first occurrence of the word on each line. If the word "Scotland" appears three times in a single sentence on one line, only the first one becomes "Tralee". By adding the g, you instruct sed to replace every single instance of the word across the entire line.
The Completed cweb3.sh Script

Here is the completed script with the red bracket placeholders filled in and the file replacement logic added.

Pay special attention to the double quotes (") used in the sed command. Double quotes allow the shell to expand the variables $OLDSTRING and $NEWSTRING into their actual values. If you used single quotes ('), sed would literally look for the text "$OLDSTRING".
Bash

#!/bin/bash

# Read in the arguments:
OLDSTRING=$1
NEWSTRING=$2

# the following gets rid of the first two arguments
shift
shift

# from now on, "all arguments" means "all arguments from 3rd one on"
# go through all arguments one by one:

for x in "$@"
do
 echo "We need to change $OLDSTRING to $NEWSTRING in file $x" 
 ls -l $x 
 
 # Send contents to sed, swap the strings, and write to tmpfile
 cat $x | sed -e "s|$OLDSTRING|$NEWSTRING|g" > tmpfile
 
 # Overwrite the original file with the modified temporary file
 cp tmpfile $x
 
 # Do another ls -l to show the file after it has been changed
 echo "After update:"
 ls -l $x
 echo 
done

# Clean up the temporary file when the loop is finished
rm tmpfile

